le in the victimization of Spanish nationals in Mauthausen. As political prisoners, their numbers and experiences differ significantly from the millions of Jews exterminated by Hitler, yet the Spaniards in Mauthausen were nevertheless objects of Nazi violence and witnesses to the Holocaust.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aConcentration camps-Social aspects-Austria-Upper Austria. 0aMauthausen (Concentration camp). 0aNazi concentration campsxSocial aspectszAustriazUpper Austria. 0aPrisoners of warzSpain. 0aPrisoners of war-Spain. 0aSpaniardszAustriazMauthausenxHistoryy20th century. 0aSpaniards-Austria-Mauthausen-History-20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPrisoners and prisons, German. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSocial aspectszSpain. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945-Prisoners and prisons, German. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945-Social aspects-Spain. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Spain & Portugal.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060679940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751295840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487512958423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487512958.jpg  a978-3-11-060679-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles